51
00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:38.170
Random variables can be considered vectors in a vector space and we can

52
00:03:38.170 --> 00:03:43.240
define inner products to obtain geometric properties of these random variables.

53
00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:49.795
If we define the inner product between two random variables between

54
00:03:49.795 --> 00:03:56.210
x and y to be the covariance between x and y,

55
00:03:56.210 --> 00:03:59.795
we see that the covariance is Symmetric,

56
00:03:59.795 --> 00:04:03.305
Positive Definite, and Linear.

57
00:04:03.305 --> 00:04:07.405
So linearity would mean that

58
00:04:07.405 --> 00:04:14.700
the covariance of lambda times x plus y and z where x,

59
00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:18.090
y and z are random variables,

60
00:04:18.090 --> 00:04:21.430
and lambda is a real number,

61
00:04:21.430 --> 00:04:26.510
is lambda times the covariance between x and

62
00:04:26.510 --> 00:04:32.790
z plus the covariance between y and z.

63
00:04:32.790 --> 00:04:39.000
And if the length of a random variable is

64
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:46.095
the square root of the covariance between of x with itself,

65
00:04:46.095 --> 00:04:52.594
which is the square root of the variance of x,

66
00:04:52.594 --> 00:04:58.525
then this is the standard deviation of the random variable x.

67
00:04:58.525 --> 00:05:05.365
So this is the length of a random variable.

68
00:05:05.365 --> 00:05:08.590
Therefore, the zero vector is a vector that has no uncertainty,

69
00:05:08.590 --> 00:05:11.635
that means standard deviation is zero.

70
00:05:11.635 --> 00:05:14.860
If we now look at the angle between two random variables,

71
00:05:14.860 --> 00:05:17.025
